Milton Friedman was a liberal too but only in the classical sense. 


Jacob Sullum: In 1994 Milton Friedman wrote a letter to Policy Review to complain that the magazine, then published by the Heritage Foundation, had inaccurately described his mentor and friend F.A. Hayek as a conservative. Noting that Hayek had included a postscript in his classic work of political philosophy The Constitution of LibertyCapitalism and Freedom, &#8220;the right and proper label&#8221; for this orientation, for &#8220;the doctrines pertaining to the free man,&#8221; is liberalism. But in the United States during the 20th century, that term &#8220;came to be associated with a readiness to rely primarily on the state rather than on private voluntary arrangements to achieve objectives regarded as desirable.&#8221;
